The <b>Streaked Shearwater</b>, <i>Calonectris leucomelas</i> is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seabird" title="Seabird">seabird</a>. The bird is 48&nbsp;cm (19&nbsp;in) in size, with a 122&nbsp;cm (48&nbsp;in) wingspan.
This species is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelagic" title="Pelagic" class="mw-redirect">pelagic</a>, but also occurs in inshore waters. It occurs in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">Pacific Ocean</a>, nesting in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a> and many of its offshore islands. After breeding, the Streaked Shearwater migrates toward southern <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>. It has been reported well off the west coast of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and from the Southern coast of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-indiacost_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-indiacost-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources" title="Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources"><span title="The material in the vicinity of this tag may rely on an unreliable source from November 2012">unreliable source</span></a></i>]</sup>
The Streaked Shearwater feeds mainly on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish" title="Fish">fish</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squid" title="Squid">squid</a>. It follows fishing boats, attracted to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anchovy" title="Anchovy">anchovy</a> crawls off Japan.
Streaked Shearwater uses <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burrow" title="Burrow">burrows</a> to nest in. It prefers forested hills.
This bird is abundant and widespread, however some mortality occurs through becoming entangled in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fishing" title="Fishing">fishing</a> nets, and from some predation by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cats" title="Cats" class="mw-redirect">cats</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rats" title="Rats" class="mw-redirect">rats</a>. In addition, it is harvested by some traditional endemic human cultures.
